
1
00:00:00.580 --> 00:00:03.370 line:15% 
<v ->Data transfer over networks.</v>

1
00:00:03,370 --> 00:00:05,300
So when we transfer data over networks,

2
00:00:05,300 --> 00:00:09,090
we have to have a way to tell it where it's going to go.

3
00:00:09,090 --> 00:00:12,000
Now we use IP addresses to get you to the system,

4
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:12,833
but how does it know what

5
00:00:12,833 --> 00:00:15,110
application is listening on that system?

6
00:00:15,110 --> 00:00:17,450
Well, that's where a port comes in,

7
00:00:17,450 --> 00:00:18,930
and ports are going to be numbered

8
00:00:18,930 --> 00:00:23,930
from zero all the way up to 65,536.

9
00:00:23,960 --> 00:00:25,330
That's a lot of ports,

10
00:00:25,330 --> 00:00:28,110
so even though you only have one IP on our machine,

11
00:00:28,110 --> 00:00:31,850
you can have over 65,000 different openings

12
00:00:31,850 --> 00:00:34,220
for you to be able to run services on.

13
00:00:34,220 --> 00:00:36,840
Now, we break these up into two buckets.

14
00:00:36,840 --> 00:00:40,120
The first is called the well-known and reserved ports.

15
00:00:40,120 --> 00:00:43,440
These are ports from zero through 1024.

16
00:00:43,440 --> 00:00:46,360
These might be things like file transfer protocol

17
00:00:46,360 --> 00:00:51,360
on port 21, web browsing on port 80, and things like that.

18
00:00:51,450 --> 00:00:53,310
Ephemeral ports, on the other hand,

19
00:00:53,310 --> 00:00:55,640
are short-lived temporary ports

20
00:00:55,640 --> 00:00:59,220
that are open for a short time from this predefined range,

21
00:00:59,220 --> 00:01:00,700
and these ports can be things

22
00:01:00,700 --> 00:01:03,680
from 1025 all the way up to 65,536.

23
00:01:06,400 --> 00:01:08,760
For example, as I'm recording this lecture,

24
00:01:08,760 --> 00:01:11,470
I record the audio on my iPad.

25
00:01:11,470 --> 00:01:13,688
The iPad then acts as a file server

26
00:01:13,688 --> 00:01:17,570
and picks a random port around 60,000ish,

27
00:01:17,570 --> 00:01:20,100
and my web browser on my laptop

28
00:01:20,100 --> 00:01:23,160
can then access that and download the audio file.

29
00:01:23,160 --> 00:01:25,800
That is opened just as long as I download the file

30
00:01:25,800 --> 00:01:28,110
and then it closes again, just that quickly.

31
00:01:29,470 --> 00:01:31,680
Now, data transfer occurs using

32
00:01:31,680 --> 00:01:34,330
these IP addresses and these ports,

33
00:01:34,330 --> 00:01:36,420
so what does this look like in the real world?

34
00:01:36,420 --> 00:01:37,670
Well, as you can see here,

35
00:01:37,670 --> 00:01:41,290
I have a client on the left and a website on the right.

36
00:01:41,290 --> 00:01:44,280
The client is at the address 192.168.1.24.

37
00:01:47,130 --> 00:01:49,700
The website is at 64.82.46.21,

38
00:01:52,810 --> 00:01:56,230
so from the client to make a request to the website,

39
00:01:56,230 --> 00:01:58,920
it's going to come from the source IP,

40
00:01:58,920 --> 00:02:02,760
that 192 address, and a port, just a random port

41
00:02:02,760 --> 00:02:05,290
it's going to pick in those ephemeral ports.

42
00:02:05,290 --> 00:02:10,290
In this case, it chose 49,163.

43
00:02:10,540 --> 00:02:13,290
It's going to send it to the destination of the website,

44
00:02:13,290 --> 00:02:17,290
which is that 64 dot-dot-dot address

45
00:02:17,290 --> 00:02:20,340
on the web server which is at Destination IP.

46
00:02:20,340 --> 00:02:21,750
What port does it go to?

47
00:02:21,750 --> 00:02:25,100
The default one for websites, which is port 80.

48
00:02:25,100 --> 00:02:28,180
Now, the website on the other hand, is going to reverse that

49
00:02:28,180 --> 00:02:31,010
and go from its source, and its port 80,

50
00:02:31,010 --> 00:02:34,690
back to the client on its random high port, 49,163.

51
00:02:36,690 --> 00:02:39,070
So you can see how this communication will happen

52
00:02:39,070 --> 00:02:42,370
to establish the session and communicate over that port.

53
00:02:42,370 --> 00:02:44,580
Whenever we're done transmitting this website,

54
00:02:44,580 --> 00:02:47,230
that random high port that was opened on your client,

55
00:02:47,230 --> 00:02:49,970
it's closed and another random one will be opened,

56
00:02:49,970 --> 00:02:52,770
but port 80 will always be sitting there on that web server

57
00:02:52,770 --> 00:02:54,720
ready to serve requests from

58
00:02:54,720 --> 00:02:56,550
anybody else who wants a website.

59
00:02:57,930 --> 00:03:01,790
Now IP version four packets are going to consist of

60
00:03:01,790 --> 00:03:04,700
the source address, that IP of the sender,

61
00:03:04,700 --> 00:03:07,820
a destination address, the IP of the receiver,

62
00:03:07,820 --> 00:03:09,690
the IP flags, which will allow

63
00:03:09,690 --> 00:03:12,500
packet fragmentation and other special things,

64
00:03:12,500 --> 00:03:16,690
and the protocol, is it going to be using TCP or UDP.

65
00:03:16,690 --> 00:03:20,840
All of those things will go to make up this packet header,

66
00:03:20,840 --> 00:03:24,500
and you can see it here shown on the screen in blue.

67
00:03:24,500 --> 00:03:26,930
Do you have to memorize this packet header?

68
00:03:26,930 --> 00:03:29,780
No, no, no, no, no, don't worry about it,

69
00:03:29,780 --> 00:03:32,060
but do understand that your header is what's going to contain

70
00:03:32,060 --> 00:03:34,950
your source and destination, as well as the port,

71
00:03:34,950 --> 00:03:37,060
the protocol, and things of that nature,

72
00:03:37,060 --> 00:03:39,220
so your packets know where to be routed to.

73
00:03:40,190 --> 00:03:42,920
Now back when we talked about TCP and UDP,

74
00:03:42,920 --> 00:03:46,680
we talked about the fact that TCP had a lot more overhead.

75
00:03:46,680 --> 00:03:48,890
Now, what does that really look like?

76
00:03:48,890 --> 00:03:51,230
Well, that's what I have here on the screen.

77
00:03:51,230 --> 00:03:56,010
Up top, we have the TCP header, which is 20 bytes in length,

78
00:03:56,010 --> 00:03:58,490
and you can see it contains things like the source port,

79
00:03:58,490 --> 00:04:01,170
the destination port, the sequence number,

80
00:04:01,170 --> 00:04:04,440
the acknowledgement number, and then a bunch of other flags.

81
00:04:04,440 --> 00:04:07,060
All of that with the checksum and the pointers,

82
00:04:07,060 --> 00:04:08,810
it all adds to this overall length,

83
00:04:08,810 --> 00:04:11,330
making it a pretty bulky protocol.

84
00:04:11,330 --> 00:04:13,660
Now compare that with UDP at the bottom.

85
00:04:13,660 --> 00:04:15,930
It only has four pieces of information,

86
00:04:15,930 --> 00:04:18,360
the source port, the destination port,

87
00:04:18,360 --> 00:04:20,820
the length of the packet, and the checksum.

88
00:04:20,820 --> 00:04:23,290
That's it, and it's only eight bytes long,

89
00:04:23,290 --> 00:04:27,290
so you can see that there's less of the data there in UDP

90
00:04:27,290 --> 00:04:28,970
because there's less that needs to be contained,

91
00:04:28,970 --> 00:04:30,010
and so it allows us to have

92
00:04:30,010 --> 00:04:32,300
a faster, more efficient protocol.
